name: Fungal Infection
description: Fungal infections, also known as mycoses, are caused by microscopic fungi that thrive in warm, moist environments.  They can affect various parts of the body, including skin, nails, and internal organs.  Common symptoms of skin-related fungal infections include intense itching, a red, scaly rash, and nodal (raised, bump-like) skin eruptions.  Dischromic patches, or areas of altered skin pigmentation (lighter or darker than the surrounding skin), can also occur.  Symptoms vary depending on the location and type of fungus.  Nail infections often present as thickening, discoloration, and brittleness.  While many fungal infections are superficial and easily treated, some can become systemic and pose a more serious health risk, especially for individuals with weakened immune systems.

name: Allergy
description: An allergy is an immune system overreaction to normally harmless substances called allergens.  Exposure to these allergens, such as pollen, pet dander, or certain foods, triggers the release of histamine and other chemicals, leading to various symptoms. While continuous sneezing and watering eyes are common allergic reactions, shivering and chills are less typical and might indicate a different issue, like an infection.  Typical allergy symptoms also include runny nose, itchy eyes, skin rash (hives), and swelling.  Severe allergies can cause anaphylaxis, a life-threatening reaction involving difficulty breathing and a drop in blood pressure, requiring immediate medical attention.

name: GERD
description: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a chronic digestive disorder where stomach acid frequently flows back into the esophagus, irritating its lining.  This backflow, known as acid reflux, happens when the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), a muscle at the bottom of the esophagus, weakens or doesn't close properly.  Common GERD symptoms include heartburn (a burning sensation in the chest), acid regurgitation (a sour or bitter taste in the mouth), and difficulty swallowing.  Other symptoms can include stomach pain, acidity, ulcers on the tongue, vomiting, chronic cough, and chest pain, which may mimic a heart attack.  While occasional heartburn is common, frequent and persistent symptoms indicate GERD and require medical attention.

name: Chronic Cholestasis
description: Chronic cholestasis is a long-term liver condition characterized by a reduction or blockage of bile flow from the liver to the small intestine.  This bile buildup in the liver leads to a variety of unpleasant symptoms.  The most common and often debilitating symptom is intense itching (pruritus).  Other symptoms include yellowish discoloration of the skin and the whites of the eyes (jaundice), nausea and vomiting, loss of appetite, and abdominal pain, particularly in the upper right quadrant.  Over time, chronic cholestasis can lead to complications like vitamin deficiencies, weakened bones, and liver damage.  The underlying causes are varied, ranging from genetic disorders and autoimmune diseases to gallstones and certain medications.

name: Drug Reaction
description: A drug reaction, also known as an adverse drug reaction (ADR) or drug allergy, is an unwanted and harmful response to a medication. Reactions can range from mild to life-threatening, and may occur immediately or develop over time. Symptoms vary widely depending on the individual and the specific drug involved.  Common symptoms include itching, skin rash (hives, blisters, or redness), and stomach pain (cramps, nausea, or vomiting).  Some reactions affect the urinary tract causing burning during urination (dysuria) and blood in the urine (hematuria, often presenting as spotting).  If you experience any of these symptoms after starting a new medication, contact your doctor or pharmacist immediately.  Severe reactions, such as difficulty breathing or swelling of the face, throat, or tongue, require emergency medical attention.

name: Peptic Ulcer Disease
description: Peptic ulcer disease (PUD) refers to painful sores or ulcers that develop in the lining of the stomach or the first part of the small intestine (duodenum).  These ulcers form when the protective mucus layer is eroded, exposing the lining to stomach acid.  Common symptoms include a burning or gnawing pain in the upper abdomen, often occurring between meals or at night.  Other symptoms can include indigestion (dyspepsia), vomiting, loss of appetite, abdominal bloating and excessive gas, and a feeling of fullness. While internal itching is not typically associated with PUD, some individuals may experience a burning sensation that could be misinterpreted as itching. If you experience persistent abdominal discomfort, consult a healthcare professional for diagnosis and treatment.

name: AIDS
description: Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS) is the late stage of HIV infection, caused by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus. HIV attacks the body's immune system, specifically CD4 cells, leaving individuals vulnerable to opportunistic infections and cancers.  While muscle wasting can occur in later stages of AIDS, and high fever can be a symptom of initial HIV infection or later opportunistic illnesses, patches in the throat (likely thrush) are a common early symptom.  It's crucial to differentiate between HIV infection and AIDS.  Extra-marital contact is a *risk factor* for HIV transmission, not a symptom of the disease itself.  Other symptoms can include swollen lymph nodes, persistent fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, and skin rashes.  A blood test is required for diagnosis.

name: Diabetes
description: Diabetes is a chronic metabolic disorder characterized by elevated blood sugar levels due to the body's inability to produce or effectively use insulin.  Type 1 diabetes results from the immune system attacking insulin-producing cells, while Type 2 diabetes develops from insulin resistance and eventual decreased production.  Common symptoms include fatigue, unexplained weight loss, restlessness, lethargy, and fluctuating blood sugar.  High blood sugar can also lead to blurred or distorted vision, excessive hunger and increased appetite (polyphagia), and frequent urination (polyuria). While obesity is a risk factor for Type 2 diabetes, it's not a direct symptom of the disease itself.  If left unmanaged, diabetes can lead to serious complications affecting the heart, kidneys, nerves, and eyes.

name: Gastroenteritis
description: Gastroenteritis, commonly known as the "stomach flu," is an inflammation of the stomach and intestines.  It's typically caused by viral or bacterial infections, though parasites and certain foods can also be culprits.  Symptoms often include vomiting and diarrhoea, leading to dehydration, which can manifest as sunken eyes.  Other signs may include abdominal cramps, nausea, fever, and muscle aches. While most cases resolve within a few days with rest and hydration, severe dehydration, especially in infants and the elderly, requires prompt medical attention.  Practicing good hygiene, such as frequent handwashing, helps prevent the spread of gastroenteritis.

name: Bronchial Asthma
description: Bronchial asthma is a chronic respiratory disease characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the airways, making breathing difficult.  Symptoms vary in frequency and intensity, and include breathlessness (especially with exertion or at night), a persistent cough (often worse at night or early morning), and wheezing.  While fatigue and mucoid sputum (thick, sticky mucus) can accompany asthma, high fever is not typically a symptom and suggests a possible infection. Family history is a risk factor, meaning individuals with asthmatic relatives are more likely to develop the condition. Asthma triggers include allergens (like pollen, dust mites, and pet dander), irritants (such as smoke and strong odors), respiratory infections, and exercise.

name: Hypertension
description: Hypertension, commonly known as high blood pressure, is a condition where the force of blood against artery walls is consistently too high, increasing the risk of serious health problems like heart attack and stroke.  While often asymptomatic, persistent elevation in blood pressure can manifest in various ways.  Symptoms may include frequent or severe headaches, chest pain (especially angina), dizziness, problems with balance, and difficulty concentrating.  These symptoms, however, can be indicative of other conditions, so it's crucial to have blood pressure regularly checked for accurate diagnosis.  Untreated hypertension can damage blood vessels and organs over time, leading to potentially life-threatening complications.

name: Migraine
description: Migraine is a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent, often severe headaches.  These headaches are typically pulsating and one-sided, ranging from moderate to debilitating intensity.  Accompanying symptoms can include nausea, vomiting, acidity, indigestion, and increased sensitivity to light and sound.  Visual disturbances are common, manifesting as blurred or distorted vision, auras (flashing lights or zigzag patterns), and even temporary vision loss.  Other associated symptoms can include excessive hunger or loss of appetite, stiff neck, depression, irritability, and difficulty concentrating.  Triggers vary widely and can include stress, certain foods, hormonal changes, and environmental factors.

name: Cervical Spondylosis
description: Cervical spondylosis, often called neck arthritis, is a common, age-related degenerative condition affecting the spinal discs and joints in the neck.  As the discs dehydrate and shrink, bone spurs can form, putting pressure on the spinal cord and nerves.  This can lead to a variety of symptoms, including neck pain and stiffness, which may radiate to the shoulders and arms.  Some individuals experience weakness or numbness in their arms and hands.  Other symptoms can include dizziness, loss of balance, and headaches. While many people with cervical spondylosis experience minimal symptoms, severe cases can cause significant pain and disability.

name: Paralysis (brain hemorrhage)
description: Paralysis resulting from a brain hemorrhage, also known as hemorrhagic stroke, occurs when a blood vessel in the brain ruptures and bleeds. This bleeding compresses surrounding brain tissue, disrupting its function and leading to various neurological deficits.  Symptoms often appear suddenly and can include a severe headache, vomiting, weakness or numbness on one side of the body (hemiparesis), and altered sensorium (confusion, decreased consciousness, or coma).  The severity of symptoms depends on the location and extent of the bleeding.  Hemorrhagic stroke is a medical emergency requiring immediate treatment to minimize brain damage.

name: Jaundice
description: Jaundice is a condition characterized by yellowing of the skin and whites of the eyes, caused by a buildup of bilirubin in the blood.  Bilirubin is a yellow pigment produced during the breakdown of red blood cells.  Jaundice itself isn't a disease, but a symptom of several underlying conditions affecting the liver, gallbladder, or pancreas.  These conditions can disrupt the normal processing of bilirubin, leading to its accumulation. Common symptoms associated with jaundice include itching, fatigue, abdominal pain, dark urine, and yellowish skin and eyes.  Other possible symptoms include vomiting, weight loss, and high fever, depending on the underlying cause.  Prompt medical attention is essential to diagnose and treat the root cause of jaundice.

name: Malaria
description: Malaria is a life-threatening disease caused by parasites transmitted to humans through the bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes.  Common symptoms include cyclical occurrences of chills, high fever, and sweating, often accompanied by headache, nausea, vomiting, muscle pain, and diarrhea.  These symptoms typically appear 10-15 days after the infective bite.  If left untreated, malaria can quickly progress to severe illness, including breathing difficulties, organ failure, and even death.  Prevention focuses on avoiding mosquito bites through the use of insecticide-treated bed nets, repellents, and antimalarial drugs.  Prompt diagnosis and treatment are essential for preventing complications.

name: Chickenpox
description: Chickenpox, also known as varicella, is a highly contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus.  It's characterized by an itchy, blistering skin rash that spreads across the body.  The rash begins as small, red spots that develop into fluid-filled blisters, eventually scabbing over.  Accompanying the rash are symptoms like fatigue, lethargy, and sometimes a mild or high fever.  Other possible symptoms include headache, loss of appetite, swollen lymph nodes, and a general feeling of malaise. While typically mild in children, chickenpox can be more severe in adults and those with weakened immune systems.

name: Dengue
description: Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne viral illness prevalent in tropical and subtropical regions. Symptoms typically appear 4-10 days after infection and range from mild to severe.  Common manifestations include a high fever, severe headache, pain behind the eyes, joint and muscle pain, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite.  A skin rash, often with red spots, may also develop.  Some individuals experience chills and a general feeling of malaise (discomfort).  In severe cases, dengue can progress to dengue hemorrhagic fever, characterized by bleeding, organ damage, and potentially death.

name: Typhoid
description: Typhoid fever, also known simply as typhoid, is a bacterial infection caused by *Salmonella* Typhi. It's typically contracted through contaminated food or water and spreads through the fecal-oral route.  Symptoms develop gradually over one to three weeks and include prolonged high fever (up to 104°F/40°C), weakness and fatigue, headache, belly pain/abdominal discomfort, loss of appetite, constipation or diarrhea, and sometimes a rose-colored rash.  In severe cases, delirium ("typhos" or toxic look) can occur. If left untreated, typhoid can lead to serious complications, including intestinal bleeding and perforation.

name: Hepatitis A
description: Hepatitis A is a highly contagious liver infection caused by the hepatitis A virus (HAV).  It's typically transmitted through contaminated food or water, or close contact with an infected person. Symptoms can range from mild to severe and may include fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, dark urine, and jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes).  Joint and muscle pain can also occur.  While most individuals recover fully, hepatitis A can occasionally cause severe liver damage.  Vaccination is available and highly effective in preventing the disease.  Good hygiene practices, such as frequent handwashing, are also crucial in preventing its spread.

name: Hepatitis B
description: Hepatitis B is a viral infection affecting the liver, potentially leading to both acute and chronic illness.  Symptoms can range from mild to severe, and some individuals may be asymptomatic. Common signs include fatigue, lethargy, malaise, loss of appetite, abdominal pain, and jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes, accompanied by dark or yellow urine).  Itching can also occur.  Hepatitis B is transmitted through contact with infected blood or other body fluids, including through receiving contaminated blood transfusions or unsterile injections, as well as from mother to child during birth.  While acute infections often resolve on their own, chronic hepatitis B can lead to serious complications like cirrhosis and liver cancer.

name: Hepatitis C
description: Hepatitis C is a liver infection caused by the hepatitis C virus (HCV), often spread through contact with infected blood.  It can range from a mild illness lasting a few weeks to a serious, lifelong infection.  Many people with HCV don't experience symptoms for years, sometimes even decades, until liver damage becomes apparent.  When symptoms *do* occur, they can include fatigue, yellowish skin (jaundice) and eyes, nausea, and loss of appetite. While family history isn't a direct cause, having a family member with HCV might indicate shared risk factors like past blood transfusions or intravenous drug use.  Chronic hepatitis C can lead to serious complications like cirrhosis and liver cancer. Fortunately, effective antiviral medications are available that can cure most people with HCV.

name: Hepatitis D
description: Hepatitis D is a serious liver infection caused by the hepatitis D virus (HDV).  It only occurs in people already infected with the hepatitis B virus (HBV), as HDV needs HBV to replicate.  HDV can either co-infect with HBV initially or infect someone already chronically infected with HBV.  Symptoms can range from mild to severe and may include fatigue, nausea, vomiting, loss of appetite, abdominal pain, yellowish skin and eyes (jaundice), dark urine, and joint pain.  The infection can become chronic, leading to severe liver damage, including cirrhosis and liver cancer.  There's no specific cure for hepatitis D, but treatment focuses on managing the HBV infection, which can help control HDV.  Vaccination against HBV is the best way to prevent hepatitis D.

name: Hepatitis E
description: Hepatitis E is a liver infection caused by the hepatitis E virus (HEV).  It's typically transmitted through contaminated food and water, particularly in areas with poor sanitation.  While often mild and self-limiting, hepatitis E can be severe, especially in pregnant women and individuals with pre-existing liver conditions.  Symptoms include fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, jaundice (yellowing of skin and eyes), dark urine, and fever. In rare cases, acute liver failure, coma, and stomach bleeding can occur.  Most people recover fully, but pregnant women are at risk of severe complications, including death.  Good hygiene practices and safe food and water consumption are crucial for prevention.

name: Alcoholic Hepatitis
description: Alcoholic hepatitis is liver inflammation caused by excessive alcohol consumption.  It can range from mild to severe.  Symptoms include vomiting, jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), abdominal pain and swelling (ascites), and abdominal distention.  Naturally, a history of heavy alcohol use is a key indicator.  Fluid retention leading to swelling in the legs and abdomen (fluid overload) is also common.  While some individuals may experience few or no symptoms, others can develop severe complications like liver failure and hepatic encephalopathy (brain dysfunction).  Prompt medical attention is crucial for diagnosis and management of alcoholic hepatitis.

name: Tuberculosis
description: Tuberculosis (TB) is a bacterial infection primarily affecting the lungs, caused by *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*. It spreads through the air when an infected person coughs, speaks, or sneezes.  Symptoms vary depending on the stage and location of the infection.  While some may experience latent TB with no symptoms, active TB commonly presents with a persistent cough (often with blood in the sputum), fever (mild to high), chills, night sweats, fatigue, weight loss, loss of appetite, and chest pain.  Breathlessness can occur with advanced lung involvement.  Swollen lymph nodes, malaise, and phlegm production are also possible.  Yellowing of the eyes is less common and may suggest liver involvement. Vomiting is not a typical TB symptom.

name: Common Cold
description: The common cold is a viral infection of the upper respiratory tract, primarily caused by rhinoviruses.  Symptoms typically appear 1-3 days after exposure and include a runny or stuffy nose, sneezing, sore throat, cough, and congestion.  Headache, mild body aches, and fatigue are also common.  While a fever can occur, it's usually low-grade.  Symptoms like high fever, chest pain, swollen lymph nodes, and loss of smell are less common and may indicate a more serious illness like the flu.  The common cold typically resolves within 7-10 days, though some symptoms may linger for longer.  Treatment focuses on relieving symptoms and includes rest, fluids, and over-the-counter medications for pain and congestion.

name: Pneumonia
description: Pneumonia is a lung infection causing inflammation in the air sacs, which can fill with fluid or pus. This interferes with oxygen uptake, leading to various symptoms. Common symptoms include chills, fatigue, a persistent cough (often producing phlegm, which may be rusty-colored), high fever, breathlessness, sweating, and a general feeling of malaise.  Chest pain, particularly when breathing deeply, and a rapid heart rate can also occur. Pneumonia can be caused by bacteria, viruses, or fungi, and its severity ranges from mild to life-threatening, especially in vulnerable populations like infants, young children, the elderly, and individuals with weakened immune systems.

name: Dimorphic Hemmorhoids (piles)
description: Dimorphic hemorrhoids, commonly known as piles, are swollen veins in the anus and rectum that can be either internal (inside the rectum) or external (under the skin around the anus).  They develop due to increased pressure in the rectal veins, often caused by straining during bowel movements, pregnancy, or chronic constipation.  Symptoms vary depending on the location and severity.  Common symptoms include constipation, painful bowel movements, persistent pain or discomfort in the anal region, bright red blood on the stool or toilet paper, and anal itching or irritation.  While often not serious, hemorrhoids can be uncomfortable and disruptive.  If symptoms are severe or persistent, medical attention should be sought.

name: Heart Attack
description: A heart attack (myocardial infarction) occurs when blood flow to the heart muscle is severely reduced or cut off, usually due to a blockage in a coronary artery. This blockage, often a blood clot formed on a plaque of cholesterol and fat, deprives the heart of oxygen, leading to damage or death of heart tissue.  Common symptoms include chest pain or discomfort, often described as pressure, tightness, or squeezing.  Other symptoms can include shortness of breath (breathlessness), nausea (sometimes leading to vomiting), and profuse sweating.  While chest pain is a hallmark symptom, some individuals, especially women, may experience a heart attack without prominent chest pain, presenting with these other symptoms instead.  A heart attack is a medical emergency requiring immediate treatment.

name: Varicose Veins
description: Varicose veins are enlarged, twisted veins that often appear blue or purple just beneath the skin's surface, most commonly in the legs and feet.  They develop when tiny valves within the veins, which help regulate blood flow back to the heart, weaken or malfunction. This causes blood to pool, increasing pressure and causing the veins to swell and become distorted.  Common symptoms include visible, prominent veins, especially on the calf, along with leg swelling, particularly around the ankles and feet.  Individuals may also experience aching, fatigue, leg cramps, a feeling of heaviness, itching around the veins, and skin discoloration or bruising. While obesity can increase the risk of developing varicose veins, it isn't a symptom itself.

name: Hypothyroidism
description: Hypothyroidism, or underactive thyroid, occurs when the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone. This hormone is crucial for regulating metabolism, affecting nearly every organ system.  Common symptoms include fatigue, unexplained weight gain, constantly feeling cold (especially hands and feet), mood swings ranging from lethargy to irritability and depression, and dizziness.  Physical changes can include a puffy face and eyes, an enlarged thyroid (goiter), brittle nails, swollen extremities, and abnormal menstrual cycles in women.  If you experience several of these symptoms, consult a doctor for diagnosis and treatment options, which typically involve hormone replacement therapy.

name: Hyperthyroidism
description: Hyperthyroidism, also known as overactive thyroid, occurs when the thyroid gland produces excessive amounts of thyroid hormones. These hormones regulate metabolism, affecting various bodily functions. Common symptoms include fatigue alongside restlessness and irritability, unexplained weight loss despite increased hunger, and a rapid or irregular heartbeat.  Heat intolerance with excessive sweating, frequent bowel movements (diarrhoea), muscle weakness, and mood swings are also typical. Women may experience changes in their menstrual cycle.  If left untreated, hyperthyroidism can lead to serious complications like heart problems and osteoporosis.  A doctor can diagnose the condition through blood tests measuring thyroid hormone levels.

name: Hypoglycemia
description: Hypoglycemia, or low blood sugar, occurs when blood glucose levels drop below the normal range.  This can happen for various reasons, including diabetes medication, excessive insulin production, skipped meals, or strenuous exercise.  Symptoms vary in severity but commonly include fatigue, anxiety, sweating, headache, nausea, and excessive hunger.  Vision can become blurred or distorted. Drying and tingling lips, slurred speech, irritability, and palpitations can also occur.  Severe hypoglycemia can lead to seizures, loss of consciousness, and even coma if left untreated.  Prompt treatment, often involving consuming sugary foods or drinks, is crucial to restoring blood glucose levels.

name: Osteoarthritis
description: Osteoarthritis (OA) is a degenerative joint disease characterized by the breakdown of cartilage, the protective tissue cushioning the ends of bones. This breakdown leads to bone-on-bone friction, causing pain, stiffness, and reduced joint mobility. Common symptoms include joint pain, particularly in weight-bearing joints like the knees and hips. Neck pain can also occur if OA affects the facet joints in the spine.  Swelling, stiffness, and painful walking are frequently experienced, with symptoms often worsening after activity or periods of inactivity.  While there's no cure for OA, various treatments can manage symptoms and improve joint function.

name: Arthritis
description: Arthritis is a general term encompassing over 100 conditions affecting joints, characterized by inflammation and pain. Symptoms vary depending on the specific type of arthritis, but commonly include joint pain, swelling, stiffness, and reduced range of motion.  Osteoarthritis, a degenerative form, involves cartilage breakdown, while rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disease where the immune system attacks the joints.  Symptoms listed like muscle weakness, stiff neck, swelling joints, movement stiffness, and painful walking can all be associated with various forms of arthritis, though muscle weakness and stiff neck may be more indicative of related conditions or complications.  Diagnosis involves physical examination, imaging, and sometimes blood tests. Treatment aims to manage pain, reduce inflammation, and improve joint function.

name: Vertigo
description: Vertigo isn't a disease itself, but a symptom of an underlying problem.  It's characterized by a false sensation of movement, often described as a spinning sensation or feeling off-balance, even when stationary.  This can lead to difficulties with balance and walking, increasing the risk of falls.  Accompanying symptoms often include nausea, vomiting, headache, and a general feeling of unsteadiness. Vertigo can range from a mild, fleeting sensation to a severe, debilitating condition.  Its causes are varied, ranging from inner ear issues like benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) to more serious conditions like migraines or neurological problems.  If experiencing vertigo, it's important to seek medical attention to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.

name: Acne
description: Acne is a common skin condition that occurs when hair follicles become clogged with oil and dead skin cells. This blockage can lead to a variety of symptoms, including whiteheads (closed comedones), blackheads (open comedones), pimples (papules and pustules), and sometimes deeper, more inflammatory lesions like nodules and cysts.  These blemishes typically appear on the face, chest, back, and shoulders.  While acne can cause scarring, particularly with severe or untreated inflammation, milder forms often resolve without permanent marks.  Symptoms vary in severity from occasional mild breakouts to persistent and widespread inflammation.

name: Urinary Tract Infection
description: A urinary tract infection (UTI) is an infection affecting any part of the urinary system, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra.  Most UTIs involve the lower urinary tract — the bladder and the urethra.  Common symptoms include a strong, persistent urge to urinate (even if little comes out), a burning sensation when urinating (dysuria), pelvic pressure or discomfort (especially in women), urine that appears cloudy, bloody, or strong-smelling, and a frequent feeling of needing to urinate.  While some UTIs resolve on their own, others require antibiotics to prevent complications like kidney infections.  If you experience these symptoms, consult a healthcare professional for diagnosis and treatment.

name: Psoriasis
description: Psoriasis is a chronic autoimmune disease that primarily affects the skin.  It causes rapid skin cell turnover, leading to raised, red, scaly patches covered with a silvery-white buildup of dead skin cells. These patches, called plaques, commonly appear on the elbows, knees, scalp, and lower back, but can occur anywhere on the body.  Symptoms vary in severity and may include skin rash, itching, burning, skin peeling, and a silver-like dusting on the plaques.  Psoriatic arthritis, a related condition, can cause joint pain and inflammation. Nail changes, such as small dents, pitting, thickening, and separation from the nail bed, are also common.

name: Impetigo
description: Impetigo is a highly contagious bacterial skin infection, primarily affecting infants and children. It's characterized by red sores, most commonly around the nose and mouth, that quickly develop into blisters filled with pus. These blisters then rupture, leaving behind honey-colored, crusty ooze.  While a skin rash is the hallmark symptom, high fever is generally *not* associated with impetigo.  Itching and some localized soreness are common.  Impetigo is easily spread through direct contact with the sores or contaminated items.  Prompt treatment with topical or oral antibiotics is crucial to prevent its spread and complications.
